the quality of your life."


212
00:09:38,612 --> 00:09:40,814 line:-2
That's a quote
from Esther Perel


213
00:09:40.848 --> 00:09:44.518 line:-2 align:center
who's a legendary
couples counselor and podcaster.


214
00:09:44.551 --> 00:09:48.922 line:-1 align:center
And, you know, it's so true


215
00:09:48.956 --> 00:09:52.392 line:-1 align:center
as to be a truism in some ways,


216
00:09:52.426 --> 00:09:54.494 line:-2 align:center
this notion
that relationships matter.


217
00:09:54.528 --> 00:09:56.697 line:-1 align:center
We are a social species.


218
00:09:56.730 --> 00:09:58.999 line:-2 align:center
The reason why,
for better or worse,


219
00:09:59,032 --> 00:10:00,234 line:-1
humans took over the planet


220
00:10:00,267 --> 00:10:01,668 line:-2
is not because
we were the strongest.


221
00:10:01,702 --> 00:10:03,170 line:-2
It was because
we could work together


222
00:10:03,203 --> 00:10:06,273 line:-2
to take down the mastodon
or whatever it was,


223
00:10:06.306 --> 00:10:08.942 line:-2 align:center
so this need
for social connection is,


224
00:10:08,976 --> 00:10:14,214 line:-2
you know, just baked
into the motherboard for us,


225
00:10:14.248 --> 00:10:16.850 line:-2 align:center
and that was my attempt
to use some sort


226
00:10:16.884 --> 00:10:18.552 line:-2 align:center
of vaguely
technological language.


227
00:10:18.585 --> 00:10:20.120 line:-2 align:center
I don't even know
if that was appropriate,


228
00:10:20.153 --> 00:10:22.389 line:-2 align:center
but, anyway,
it's baked into our DNA


229
00:10:22.422 --> 00:10:24.825 line:-2 align:center
and so--
but it's easily overlooked


230
00:10:24.858 --> 00:10:26.727 line:-2 align:center
at a time--
especially in the West


231
00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:30.531 line:-2 align:center
when there's such an emphasis
on individual achievement


232
00:10:30,564 --> 00:10:32,766 line:-2
and we tend to live
away from our families —


233
00:10:32,799 --> 00:10:35,602 line:-2
and the number of people who say
they have close confidants


234
00:10:35.636 --> 00:10:38.405 line:-1 align:center
has declined over time —


235
00:10:38,438 --> 00:10:41,909 line:-2
and many of us have our nose
in screens all the time —


236
00:10:41,942 --> 00:10:45,279 line:-2
that there's a way in which
we can deemphasize the value


237
00:10:45,312 --> 00:10:47,314 line:-2
of relationships —
and we have just run


238
00:10:47.347 --> 00:10:50.984 line:-1 align:center
a global unregulated experiment


239
00:10:51.018 --> 00:10:54.621 line:-2 align:center
in what happens
when you deny social connection,


240
00:10:54,655 --> 00:10:57,424 line:-2
and the results
are really clear…


241
00:10:57.457 --> 00:11:00.060 line:-2 align:center
massive spikes
in anxiety, depression,


242
00:11:00.093 --> 00:11:01.528 line:-1 align:center
addiction, and suicide.


243
00:11:01,562 --> 00:11:03,030 line:-2
[Jeff]
Oh, my God, absolutely.


244
00:11:03.063 --> 00:11:04.565 line:-2 align:center
[Dan] I think something
that a lot of people


245
00:11:04.598 --> 00:11:06.533 line:-1 align:center
are struggling with now


246
00:11:06.567 --> 00:11:09.102 line:-2 align:center
after this long period
of lockdown,


247
00:11:09,136 --> 00:11:12,406 line:-2
which, for many of us,
is not over —


248
00:11:12.439 --> 00:11:14.441 line:-2 align:center
in some parts of the world,
we're emerging from lockdown —


249
00:11:14,474 --> 00:11:16,510 line:-2
in some parts of the world,
we're really still in it —


250
00:11:16,543 --> 00:11:18,512 line:-2
but social anxiety
is a real issue.


251
00:11:18,545 --> 00:11:20,447 line:-2
It was a real issue
going into the pandemic


252
00:11:20.480 --> 00:11:22.816 line:-2 align:center
and I would imagine
even more so now.


253
00:11:22,850 --> 00:11:25,219 line:-2
Do you have any thoughts
about how to manage that?


254
00:11:25.252 --> 00:11:27.588 line:-2 align:center
[Jeff]
I would say a couple things.


255
00:11:27.621 --> 00:11:31.491 line:-2 align:center
The first is a seated practice
of five or ten minutes


256
00:11:31.525 --> 00:11:34.027 line:-2 align:center
of just getting relaxed
will center you


257
00:11:34,061 --> 00:11:35,829 line:-1
and make you--and, you know,


258
00:11:35.863 --> 00:11:37.531 line:-2 align:center
help you manage
that anxiety a little bit more.


259
00:11:37.564 --> 00:11:40.334 line:-2 align:center
I mean, that's just a kind of
a no-brainer


260
00:11:40,367 --> 00:11:41,835 line:-1
from my perspective.


261
00:11:41.869 --> 00:11:46.807 line:-2 align:center
Another thing is to get clear
about what is


262
00:11:46.840 --> 00:11:49.610 line:-2 align:center
actually making you anxious
and share that


263
00:11:49,643 --> 00:11:51,311 line:-2
with the people that you need
to hang out with.


264
00:11:51,345 --> 00:11:53,347 line:-2
So this is, again,
where the mindfulness thing


265
00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:54.581 line:-1 align:center
can be useful.


266
00:11:54.615 --> 00:11:56.884 line:-2 align:center
You know, we may
have a specific anxiety


267
00:11:56.917 --> 00:11:58.619 line:-1 align:center
'cause, you know,


268
00:11:58.652 --> 00:12:01.188 line:-2 align:center
you have some friends that want
to suddenly abandon the masks


269
00:12:01,221 --> 00:12:03,624 line:-2
and start hugging way sooner
than you're ready to do it,


270
00:12:03.657 --> 00:12:06.260 line:-2 align:center
or you're worried about the--
you have specific anxieties


271
00:12:06.293 --> 00:12:09.029 line:-2 align:center
about travel or you're--
whatever it is,


272
00:12:09.062 --> 00:12:11.064 line:-2 align:center
like, you
have a specific anxiety,


273
00:12:11.098 --> 00:12:14.168 line:-2 align:center
but until you actually
look and notice what it is,


274
00:12:14.201 --> 00:12:15.502 line:-1 align:center
that thing will own you


275
00:12:15.536 --> 00:12:17.571 line:-2 align:center
in a kind of a vague,
generalized way.


276
00:12:17.604 --> 00:12:19.039 line:-2 align:center
You'll just know
you don't really want


277
00:12:19.072 --> 00:12:20.140 line:-1 align:center
to go outside around people.


278
00:12:20.174 --> 00:12:21.942 line:-2 align:center
You won't really have
a good excuse for what it is,


279
00:12:21.975 --> 00:12:23.443 line:-1 align:center
or you can't really--you know,


280
00:12:23,477 --> 00:12:25,779 line:-2
you're just--because you
haven't brought clarity


281
00:12:25,812 --> 00:12:27,447 line:-2
to what's actually going
on in your experience.


282
00:12:27.481 --> 00:12:30.751 line:-2 align:center
So taking the time
to really identify,


283
00:12:30.784 --> 00:12:33.187 line:-2 align:center
what is
it that I'm worried about?


284
00:12:33.220 --> 00:12:34.988 line:-2 align:center
Can I--what
is the specific thing?


285
00:12:35,022 --> 00:12:37,624 line:-2
And then, based on that,
having conversations


286
00:12:37.658 --> 00:12:40.460 line:-2 align:center
with the people in your life
around--if there's any protocols


287
00:12:40,494 --> 00:12:42,996 line:-2
you might be able
to collectively agree on.


288
00:12:43,030 --> 00:12:47,100 line:-2
I mean, that's--it may sound
so common-sense,


289
00:12:47,134 --> 00:12:51,038 line:-2
but I think this is, again,
the great move of practice,


290
00:12:51.071 --> 00:12:54.374 line:-2 align:center
the great move of mindfulness
is to begin to actually


291
00:12:54,408 --> 00:12:56,643 line:-2
clarify what's really going on
in your experience,


292
00:12:56.677 --> 00:12:58.312 line:-2 align:center
and we may hear that
and think, "Oh, yeah,


293
00:12:58.345 --> 00:12:59.313 line:-1 align:center
that makes sense."


294
00:12:59,346 --> 00:13:00,747 line:-2
But we don't realize
that we're subject


295
00:13:00,781 --> 00:13:03,217 line:-2
to this kind of
unconscious thing all the time,


296
00:13:03.250 --> 00:13:05.285 line:-2 align:center
that we're
not actually doing that.


297
00:13:05.319 --> 00:13:06.854 line:-1 align:center
We don't have a lot of clarity


298
00:13:06.887 --> 00:13:08.822 line:-2 align:center
about what would
actually help us.


299
00:13:08,856 --> 00:13:11,959 line:-2
[Dan] People may be wondering,
"OK, how do I do this?


300
00:13:11.992 --> 00:13:14.261 line:-1 align:center
How do I start meditating?"


301
00:13:14.294 --> 00:13:16.797 line:-2 align:center
And often,
the question people have is,


302
00:13:16.830 --> 00:13:19.299 line:-2 align:center
"What's the least amount
I can do


303
00:13:19.333 --> 00:13:21.835 line:-2 align:center
and get all of
the advertised benefits?"


304
00:13:21.869 --> 00:13:23.837 line:-2 align:center
What's your recommendation
for folks


305
00:13:23.871 --> 00:13:25.506 line:-2 align:center
who are trying to boot up
a habit?


306
00:13:26.673 --> 00:13:28.709 line:-1 align:center
- Five minutes, ten minutes?


307
00:13:28.742 --> 00:13:32.279 line:-2 align:center
I mean, what you want is to give
your nervous system a taste.


308
00:13:32.312 --> 00:13:36.717 line:-2 align:center
So I would say just start
with five minutes a day.


309
00:13:36.750 --> 00:13:40.954 line:-2 align:center
And just--and then, you know,
let the practice inform you.


310
00:13:40.988 --> 00:13:42.823 line:-2 align:center
If you do five minutes
and, you know,


311
00:13:42,856 --> 00:13:43,857 line:-1
you can play around with--


312
00:13:43.891 --> 00:13:45.626 line:-2 align:center
I mean, the basic strategy
is just to sit


313
00:13:45,659 --> 00:13:47,327 line:-2
and notice your breath,
but you can play around


314
00:13:47.361 --> 00:13:48.996 line:-2 align:center
with other objects,
something else


315
00:13:49,029 --> 00:13:50,797 line:-2
that's just whatever,
for whatever reason,


316
00:13:50.831 --> 00:13:52.165 line:-1 align:center
is interesting to you.


317
00:13:52,199 --> 00:13:53,901 line:-2
But take five minutes
and see if you can


318
00:13:53,934 --> 00:13:56,303 line:-2
completely commit yourself
in that way,


319
00:13:56,336 --> 00:13:58,839 line:-2
and then notice--do you feel
a little bit more settled after?


320
00:13:58,872 --> 00:14:01,175 line:-2
If you do, then that's
a good place to begin.


321
00:14:01.208 --> 00:14:04.545 line:-2 align:center
And then, you know, I--
there's value


322
00:14:04.578 --> 00:14:06.146 line:-1 align:center
to moving it up from there,


323
00:14:06,180 --> 00:14:08,549 line:-2
but sometimes
five minutes a day is all I get,


324
00:14:08,582 --> 00:14:10,217 line:-2
but I'm gonna actually
throw it back to you,


325
00:14:10,250 --> 00:14:11,251 line:-2
Dan, 'cause
I know you're, like,


326
00:14:11,285 --> 00:14:15,088 line:-2
the expert at getting
regular folks to meditate.


327
00:14:15,122 --> 00:14:17,124 line:-2
So what's
your advice around this?


328
00:14:17.157 --> 00:14:19.459 line:-2 align:center
[Dan] I'll lower
the bar even further.


329
00:14:19,493 --> 00:14:23,430 line:-2
Try to meditate
for at least one minute


330
00:14:23.463 --> 00:14:26.733 line:-1 align:center
on 25 out of 31 days.


331
00:14:26.767 --> 00:14:29.002 line:-2 align:center
And this is actually
backed by science.


332
00:14:29.036 --> 00:14:31.839 line:-2 align:center
What we know
about habit formation


333
00:14:31,872 --> 00:14:35,275 line:-2
is that it is
infernally difficult


334
00:14:35,309 --> 00:14:37,945 line:-2
and that the best way
to approach it


335
00:14:37.978 --> 00:14:40.647 line:-2 align:center
is with a sense of humor,
a sense of exploration,


336
00:14:40.681 --> 00:14:42.182 line:-1 align:center
and a sense of humility,


337
00:14:42,216 --> 00:14:44,251 line:-2
that it's hard for everybody,
including you,


338
00:14:44.284 --> 00:14:48.555 line:-2 align:center
and so if you set the bar low,
you're more likely to succeed,


339
00:14:48,589 --> 00:14:50,657 line:-2
and so we have
these two little slogans


340
00:14:50.691 --> 00:14:53.927 line:-2 align:center
that kind of govern
our approach,


341
00:14:53.961 --> 00:14:55.362 line:-2 align:center
and actually I came up
with these slogans


342
00:14:55.395 --> 00:14:57.197 line:-2 align:center
while working with you, Jeff,
on our book,


343
00:14:57.231 --> 00:14:59.233 line:-2 align:center
"Meditation
for Fidgety Skeptics."


344
00:14:59.266 --> 00:15:02.402 line:-2 align:center
One slogan is
"One minute counts."


345
00:15:02,436 --> 00:15:03,804 line:-2
Yes, I would love
to see you


346
00:15:03.837 --> 00:15:06.006 line:-2 align:center
do five to ten minutes,
even more,


347
00:15:06,039 --> 00:15:09,343 line:-2
but let's be honest, again,
given what I said,


348
00:15:09.376 --> 00:15:11.879 line:-2 align:center
what we all know
about habit formation


349
00:15:11.912 --> 00:15:14.348 line:-1 align:center
being difficult, one minute--


350
00:15:14.381 --> 00:15:16.750 line:-2 align:center
in one minute
you can get a sense


351
00:15:16,783 --> 00:15:19,186 line:-1
of how wild the mind is,


352
00:15:19,219 --> 00:15:21,388 line:-2
and therefore you have
a little bit of a leg up


353
00:15:21,421 --> 00:15:23,790 line:-2
in dealing with
all of the terrible ideas


354
00:15:23,824 --> 00:15:25,492 line:-2
that the voice in your head
is offering up


355
00:15:25,526 --> 00:15:26,827 line:-1
to you on the regular.


356
00:15:26,860 --> 00:15:30,030 line:-2
And then the other
little slogan is "daily-ish."


357
00:15:30,063 --> 00:15:31,798 line:-2
Again, I would love
to see you do this every day.


358
00:15:31.832 --> 00:15:34.735 line:-2 align:center
I try to do it every day,
but if you tell yourself,


359
00:15:34.768 --> 00:15:36.370 line:-1 align:center
"I am gonna do this every day,"


360
00:15:36,403 --> 00:15:37,838 line:-1
and then you miss a day,


361
00:15:37,871 --> 00:15:40,474 line:-2
there is some
reasonable likelihood


362
00:15:40,507 --> 00:15:42,309 line:-2
that the voice in your head
will swoop in


363
00:15:42,342 --> 00:15:44,444 line:-2
and tell you, "Well,
you're a failed meditator now.


364
00:15:44.478 --> 00:15:45.946 line:-1 align:center
Deuces, I'm out."


365
00:15:45,979 --> 00:15:49,583 line:-2
And so "daily-ish" provides
what the psychologists call


366
00:15:49.616 --> 00:15:51.485 line:-1 align:center
psychological flexibility.


367
00:15:51.518 --> 00:15:53.387 line:-2 align:center
It's a kind of elasticity
that allows you


368
00:15:53,420 --> 00:15:57,291 line:-2
to start over,
and that resiliency,


369
00:15:57.324 --> 00:15:59.359 line:-2 align:center
the capacity
to start over, is so key


370
00:15:59.393 --> 00:16:01.862 line:-1 align:center
in a meditation practice


371
00:16:01.895 --> 00:16:03.263 line:-2 align:center
while you're
actually meditating,


372
00:16:03.297 --> 00:16:06.767 line:-2 align:center
and it is so key when it comes
to starting any habit


373
00:16:06.800 --> 00:16:09.803 line:-2 align:center
that you have to--
because it's so hard


374
00:16:09,837 --> 00:16:12,306 line:-1
to do this, you have to be able


375
00:16:12.339 --> 00:16:14.541 line:-2 align:center
to pick yourself up
after three weeks


376
00:16:14,575 --> 00:16:16,977 line:-2
of not meditating
or three weeks of not exercising


377
00:16:17,010 --> 00:16:18,445 line:-2
and say,
"OK, nothing's been lost.


378
00:16:18.478 --> 00:16:20.314 line:-1 align:center
I can just start again."


379
00:16:20.347 --> 00:16:22.015 line:-2 align:center
So I know
I lowered the bar there, Jeff,


380
00:16:22,049 --> 00:16:23,150 line:-1
from what you said.


381
00:16:23,183 --> 00:16:26,019 line:-2
Does that give you--
does that give you hives?


382
00:16:26.053 --> 00:16:27.354 line:-2 align:center
[Jeff]
No, not at all.


383
00:16:27.387 --> 00:16:28.722 line:-1 align:center
I mean, I use the same thing,


384
00:16:28,755 --> 00:16:32,259 line:-2
so I think it's exactly--
I mean, do what works.


385
00:16:32.292 --> 00:16:34.561 line:-2 align:center
Do whatever you can
to start to kind of get into it,


386
00:16:34,595 --> 00:16:36,597 line:-2
get a bit of a taste of it,
and I think one minute is--


387
00:16:36.630 --> 00:16:39.399 line:-2 align:center
if that can give you
a taste of it, perfect.


388
00:16:39.433 --> 00:16:42.503 line:-2 align:center
[Dan] So since we keep talking
about meditation, Jeff,


389
00:16:42.536 --> 00:16:45.439 line:-2 align:center
it may make sense to me--
if you're up for it,


390
00:16:45,472 --> 00:16:48,141 line:-2
to--let's just do
just a few minutes


391
00:16:48,175 --> 00:16:50,277 line:-2
of it 'cause I think
once people have a sense


392
00:16:50,310 --> 00:16:53,380 line:-2
of how simple this is
and how doable it is--


393
00:16:53.413 --> 00:16:55.415 line:-1 align:center
are you game for that?


394
00:16:55.449 --> 00:16:57.284 line:-2 align:center
[Jeff]
Oh, yes, I am.


395
00:17:01,288 --> 00:17:03,257 line:-2
In fact,
I was thinking--


396
00:17:03,290 --> 00:17:05,559 line:-2
I'm gonna guide a dead-simple,
five minute meditation,


397
00:17:05.592 --> 00:17:09.663 line:-2 align:center
but I'm gonna do it
with our audience in mind,


398
00:17:09.696 --> 00:17:13.333 line:-2 align:center
knowing that we have
a group of creatives


399
00:17:13.367 --> 00:17:15.702 line:-1 align:center
and developers and programmers.


400
00:17:15,736 --> 00:17:19,039 line:-1
I'm gonna use this metaphor


401
00:17:19.072 --> 00:17:20.974 line:-1 align:center
that I'll thread into it


402
00:17:21.008 --> 00:17:23.177 line:-2 align:center
that will hopefully speak
to that audience


403
00:17:23,210 --> 00:17:26,380 line:-2
and help actually dramatize
what it is we're doing.


404
00:17:26.413 --> 00:17:29.483 line:-2 align:center
So that's the five-minute
meditation intro.


405
00:17:29,516 --> 00:17:33,287 line:-1
So go ahead and close your eyes.


406
00:17:33,320 --> 00:17:35,489 line:-2
Get yourself into,
you know, whatever position


407
00:17:35.522 --> 00:17:37.691 line:-1 align:center
just feels comfortable.


408
00:17:37.724 --> 00:17:39.793 line:-2 align:center
Actually, you can even
have them open if you like,


409
00:17:39.826 --> 00:17:40.961 line:-2 align:center
looking at the ground
in front of you.


410
00:17:40.994 --> 00:17:42.663 line:-1 align:center
It's sort of user's choice.


411
00:17:44.097 --> 00:17:47.100 line:-2 align:center
Now if you're closing
your eyes or open,


412
00:17:47,134 --> 00:17:48,669 line:-2
you start
with a few deep breaths…


413
00:17:50.637 --> 00:17:53.874 line:-2 align:center
stretching out the spine
on the inhale…


414
00:17:53.907 --> 00:17:55.642 line:-2 align:center
and then the exhale
is kind of like


415
00:17:55,676 --> 00:17:58,946 line:-2
your "ahhhhh…”
Super relaxing.


416
00:17:58.979 --> 00:18:02.616 line:-2 align:center
Sending a wave of relaxation
down through the body,


417
00:18:02,649 --> 00:18:06,720 line:-2
meaning deliberately
softening your forehead...


418
00:18:06.753 --> 00:18:09.756 line:-1 align:center
and your shoulders...


419
00:18:09,790 --> 00:18:10,791 line:-1
and your belly.


420
00:18:13.894 --> 00:18:15.596 line:-2 align:center
With each exhale,
you can imagine


421
00:18:15.629 --> 00:18:18.265 line:-2 align:center
you're, you know,
settling a little more,


422
00:18:18.298 --> 00:18:20.734 line:-2 align:center
landing a little more
in your chair


423
00:18:20,767 --> 00:18:22,202 line:-1
or wherever you're sitting.


424
00:18:27.074 --> 00:18:28.442 line:-2 align:center
And the first thing
I like to do


425
00:18:28.475 --> 00:18:30.444 line:-2 align:center
at the very start
of the meditation


426
00:18:30.477 --> 00:18:34.281 line:-2 align:center
is--it's sort of tuning in
with this internal adjustment,


427
00:18:34.314 --> 00:18:36.884 line:-2 align:center
the equanimity adjustment,
which just means


428
00:18:36.917 --> 00:18:39.520 line:-2 align:center
the "letting everything be here"
adjustment.


429
00:18:39.553 --> 00:18:42.623 line:-2 align:center
So you're not gonna get uptight
about sounds being imperfect


430
00:18:42,656 --> 00:18:46,126 line:-2
in your environment or the fact
that you might have lots


431
00:18:46.159 --> 00:18:47.961 line:-2 align:center
of thoughts
or very few thoughts


432
00:18:47,995 --> 00:18:51,265 line:-1
or your body's uncomfortable.


433
00:18:51.298 --> 00:18:53.400 line:-2 align:center
It's all--the idea
is that you're just gonna


434
00:18:53,433 --> 00:18:54,768 line:-1
let all this be there.


435
00:18:56,870 --> 00:19:00,140 line:-2
We're kind of embracing
the imperfection of life,


436
00:19:00,174 --> 00:19:03,010 line:-2
and that actually is palpable
as an adjustment.


437
00:19:03,043 --> 00:19:05,546 line:-2
It's sort of, like, this--
the other way of being is


438
00:19:05.579 --> 00:19:07.881 line:-2 align:center
a kind of uptightness.
[growls]


439
00:19:07.915 --> 00:19:11.818 line:-2 align:center
Instead, just kind of
melting everything.


440
00:19:11.852 --> 00:19:14.354 line:-1 align:center
So sounds just pass through you.


441
00:19:14.388 --> 00:19:17.291 line:-2 align:center
Body sensations and thoughts
rise and fall.


442
00:19:17,324 --> 00:19:18,325 line:-1
It's all good.


443
00:19:20.694 --> 00:19:24.198 line:-2 align:center
And then we settle
into this creaturely pose.


444
00:19:26.233 --> 00:19:28.068 line:-1 align:center
Maybe feeling the breath.


445
00:19:31,738 --> 00:19:35,209 line:-2
And what's happening here is--
it's like our experience


446
00:19:35.242 --> 00:19:37.411 line:-1 align:center
has all these different layers.


447
00:19:44,017 --> 00:19:46,520 line:-2
And there's sort of
an "into it" quality


448
00:19:46.553 --> 00:19:47.521 line:-1 align:center
in meditation.


449
00:19:47,554 --> 00:19:51,024 line:-2
Sort of one of the secrets
is you choose.


450
00:19:51.058 --> 00:19:52.326 line:-1 align:center
You decide.


451
00:19:52.359 --> 00:19:54.261 line:-2 align:center
Not only are you choosing
which layer to pay attention to.


452
00:19:54.294 --> 00:19:56.830 line:-2 align:center
You're kind of choosing
to maybe a little bit


453
00:19:56.864 --> 00:20:01.535 line:-2 align:center
enjoy this opportunity
to take a break.


454
00:20:02.769 --> 00:20:04.938 line:-2 align:center
Seeing if you can kind of
get into the feeling


455
00:20:04.972 --> 00:20:07.274 line:-2 align:center
of breathing
like you're kind of into it.


456
00:20:11.578 --> 00:20:13.447 line:-2 align:center
You know,
if we make it enjoyable,


457
00:20:13,480 --> 00:20:15,616 line:-2
you're just gonna want
to meditate more,


458
00:20:15.649 --> 00:20:18.886 line:-2 align:center
as opposed to making it
some grim endurance test.


459
00:20:25.259 --> 00:20:28.095 line:-2 align:center
The mind wanders.
Totally natural.


460
00:20:28.128 --> 00:20:33.367 line:-2 align:center
You notice 'cause you've got
this awareness thing going on.


461
00:20:33,400 --> 00:20:35,736 line:-2
You notice that layer
that got activated


462
00:20:35.769 --> 00:20:37.204 line:-1 align:center
that superimposed itself


463
00:20:37.237 --> 00:20:40.607 line:-2 align:center
over top of the breath
and kind of drifted away,


464
00:20:40,641 --> 00:20:43,911 line:-2
and then you come back
to the breath layer.


465
00:20:46.280 --> 00:20:48.815 line:-2 align:center
And you let the thought
just play out on its own.


466
00:20:48.849 --> 00:20:50.184 line:-1 align:center
Now you're not feeding it.


467
00:20:52.119 --> 00:20:53.287 line:-1 align:center
It doesn't have to go away.


468
00:20:53,320 --> 00:20:54,755 line:-2
You're not trying
to get rid of thinking.


469
00:20:54,788 --> 00:20:57,591 line:-2
That thinking process
will just keep unspooling.


470
00:21:02,863 --> 00:21:05,766 line:-2
So just for fun here -
we're working with our layers -


471
00:21:05.799 --> 00:21:09.603 line:-2 align:center
we just select
this item in the menu,


472
00:21:09.636 --> 00:21:11.939 line:-2 align:center
in the drop-down menu,
one of the tools —


473
00:21:11,972 --> 00:21:14,842 line:-1
the good-naturedness tool.


474
00:21:14,875 --> 00:21:16,510 line:-1
Make sure that's selected.


475
00:21:16.543 --> 00:21:19.079 line:-2 align:center
It's kind of like you're kind of
putting a warm glow


476
00:21:19.112 --> 00:21:21.448 line:-2 align:center
over everything,
so you're just kind of--


477
00:21:21.481 --> 00:21:23.183 line:-1 align:center
you're enjoying your experience.


478
00:21:28,488 --> 00:21:31,658 line:-2
I'm going to risk
a 20-second silence here


479
00:21:31.692 --> 00:21:33.327 line:-1 align:center
before we wrap it up,


480
00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:34.394 line:-1 align:center
then I'll come in at the end,


481
00:21:34,428 --> 00:21:37,497 line:-1
but just seeing how fully


482
00:21:37.531 --> 00:21:39.933 line:-1 align:center
you can commit yourself to this.


483
00:21:39.967 --> 00:21:41.735 line:-1 align:center
Some sensation in the body.


484
00:21:50,711 --> 00:21:54,481 line:-2
The more we feel
what's here in the body,


485
00:21:54.515 --> 00:21:59.253 line:-2 align:center
things start to settle.
Sensations get subtler.


486
00:21:59,286 --> 00:22:00,821 line:-1
As we get more still,


487
00:22:00.854 --> 00:22:03.257 line:-2 align:center
our experience
often gets more still —


488
00:22:04.791 --> 00:22:08.228 line:-2 align:center
and then a thought
comes and takes us away.


489
00:22:08,262 --> 00:22:10,430 line:-1
That layer gets activated.


490
00:22:10,464 --> 00:22:11,698 line:-2
We notice.
We come back.


491
00:22:11.732 --> 00:22:15.068 line:-2 align:center
And that's the--
that's the movement of practice.


492
00:22:15,102 --> 00:22:19,406 line:-2
The movement is committing,
getting distracted,


493
00:22:19,439 --> 00:22:21,875 line:-2
recommitting,
and then suffusing


494
00:22:21,909 --> 00:22:26,647 line:-2
the proceedings with a kind of
equanimous good-naturedness.


495
00:22:28,448 --> 00:22:32,586 line:-2
So I'll just let us have
a few more seconds here.


496
00:22:42.596 --> 00:22:45.566 line:-2 align:center
And then as we prepare
to move out


497
00:22:45.599 --> 00:22:48.435 line:-2 align:center
of this
extremely short meditation,


498
00:22:48,468 --> 00:22:53,207 line:-2
just notice…
Do you feel more settled?


499
00:22:54,775 --> 00:22:56,543 line:-1
… More present?


500
00:22:56.577 --> 00:22:59.179 line:-2 align:center
And that's
the litmus test ultimately.


501
00:22:59.213 --> 00:23:01.915 line:-2 align:center
How is it--how do you
bring the practice back?


502
00:23:06.253 --> 00:23:09.489 line:-2 align:center
Now when you're ready,
open your eyes.


503
00:23:17.564 --> 00:23:18.732 line:-2 align:center
[Dan]
Thank you, Jeff.


504
00:23:20,868 --> 00:23:23,770 line:-2
There were two things
you emphasized, at least,


505
00:23:23.804 --> 00:23:25.739 line:-1 align:center
in that meditation


506
00:23:25.772 --> 00:23:28.575 line:-2 align:center
that I want
to kind of just reemphasize.


507
00:23:28.609 --> 00:23:32.913 line:-2 align:center
One is the immense benefit
of getting out


508
00:23:32,946 --> 00:23:36,116 line:-1
of your head and into your body.


509
00:23:37,985 --> 00:23:42,122 line:-2
It's--this is sadly a bit
of a cliché, you know,


510
00:23:42.155 --> 00:23:43.824 line:-2 align:center
the body knows,
et cetera, et cetera,


511
00:23:43.857 --> 00:23:46.460 line:-2 align:center
but there's a reason
why clichés become clichés,


512
00:23:46.493 --> 00:23:48.495 line:-1 align:center
and that's because they're true.


513
00:23:48,529 --> 00:23:52,666 line:-2
And I love this word you used
where you get us to kind of


514
00:23:52,699 --> 00:23:55,502 line:-2
get in touch
with the creaturely feeling


515
00:23:55.536 --> 00:23:57.938 line:-1 align:center
of having a body.


516
00:23:57.971 --> 00:24:02.142 line:-2 align:center
Most of us, you know, we're like
Macy's Day parade balloons.


517
00:24:02,176 --> 00:24:04,945 line:-2
We're just all head
floating through the world


518
00:24:04,978 --> 00:24:07,948 line:-2
with a tiny little body
just dragged beneath it,


519
00:24:07.981 --> 00:24:12.386 line:-2 align:center
but actually there's
enormous potential


520
00:24:12.419 --> 00:24:14.655 line:-2 align:center
to getting out
of the spinning stories,


521
00:24:14,688 --> 00:24:16,590 line:-2
which are
mostly past and future,


522
00:24:16,623 --> 00:24:20,127 line:-2
and into your body.
It can be really calming.


523
00:24:20.160 --> 00:24:22.763 line:-1 align:center
The other thing you talked about


524
00:24:22.796 --> 00:24:25.432 line:-1 align:center
is the fact that we are


525
00:24:25.465 --> 00:24:27.334 line:-2 align:center
